ter 10 Benny Chan’s Connected and the Hollywoodisation of Hong Kong Cinema -- tChapter 11 Vessels and Cargos: Spaces of Inclusion and Exclusion in Johnnie To’s Drug War and Lee Hae-young’s Korean Remake Believer -- tPart IV Local Flavours and Transcultural Flows in East Asian Comedies, Dramas and Fantasies -- tChapter 12 The Power of Healing in Little Forest(s): Cross-Cultural Perspectives on Food, Friendship and Self-identity, from Japan to Korea -- tChapter 13 More than Blue and Man in Love: Transnational Korean-Taiwanese Film Remakes as a Facilitator for Taiwan Cinema -- tChapter 14 The Pan-Asian ‘Miss Granny’ Phenomenon -- tChapter 15 Remaking in the Age of Chthulumedia: Stephen Chow’s The Mermaid -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConsiders the remake from a variety of critical and theoretical perspectives and positions it alongside other serialized cultural formsExamines the historical significance of the remake in revitalizing local industries and breathing life into established film genres (e.g., action-adventure, crime drama, romantic comedy, the Western, etc.)Draws attention to previously overlooked motion pictures produced in East Asia and acknowledges the significant contributions of several prolific yet neglected filmmakersRe-evaluates canonical texts and offers fresh assessments of legendary auteurs such as Ozu Yasujiro, Yu Hyun-mok, Miike Takashi, Johnnie To, and Stephen ChowShowcases the role of remakes in forging cross-cultural alliances — both within and beyond the East Asian region — while pointing toward prospects of increased transnational coproductions in the coming yearsThis wide-ranging, historically grounded exploration of motion picture remakes produced in East Asia brings together original contributions from experts in Chinese, Hong Kong, Japanese, South Korean, and Taiwanese cinemas and puts forth new ways of thinking about the remaking process as both a critically underappreciated form of artistic expression and an economically motivated industrial practice. Exploring everything from ethnic Korean filmmaker Lee Sang-il’s Unforgiven (2013), a Japanese remake of Clint Eastwood’s Western of the same title, to Stephen Chow’s The Mermaid (2016), a Chinese slapstick reimagining of Walt Disney’s The Little Mermaid (1989) and Hans Christian Andersen’s 1837 fairy tale, East Asian Film Remakes contributes to a better understanding of cinematic remaking across the region and offers vital alternatives to the Eurocentric and Hollywood-focused approaches that have thus far dominated the field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh1 aAmit, Rea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBettinson, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Kenneth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChoe, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoi, Jinhee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoates, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiffrient, David Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiffrient, David Scott, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGonzález-López, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrossman, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHsieh, Hsin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Earl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab